    "contenu": "The document provides detailed information about the most important Bordeaux wines, categorizing them as \"Leading Appellations\" and \"Appellations of Note.\" Below I have structured the content for clarity:\n\n---\n\n# THE MOST IMPORTANT BORDEAUX WINES\n\n## LEADING APPELLATIONS\n- **BARSAC** white (dry and sweet)\n- **GRAVES** white and red\n- **MARGAUX** red\n- **PAUILLAC** red\n- **PESSAC-LÉOGNAN** white and red\n- **POMEROL** red\n- **ST.-ÉMILION** red\n- **ST.-ESTÈPHE** red\n- **ST.-JULIEN** red\n- **SAUTERNES** white (dry and sweet)\n\n## APPELLATIONS OF NOTE\n- **CANON-FRONSAC** red\n- **CÔTES DE BORDEAUX** red\n- **CÔTES DE BOURG** red\n- **CÔTES DE CASTILLON** red\n- **CÔTES DE FRANCS** red\n- **ENTRE-DEUX-MERS** white\n- **FRONSAC** red\n- **LISTRAC** red\n- **MOULIS** red\n- **PREMIÈRES CÔTES DE BLAYE** red\n\n## Additional Information\n- Together, merlot and cabernet sauvignon make up more than 80 percent of all the vineyard land devoted to red grapes in Bordeaux. Cabernet franc contributes slightly over 10 percent and is considered Bordeaux’s third most important variety.\n- All other red varieties (carmenère, malbec, petit verdot) are only planted in tiny amounts.\n- The primary genetic origins for Bordeaux’s red varieties are in the southwestern quadrant of France, with the exception of cabernet franc which has roots in Spanish Basque origin.\n- For white Bordeaux wines, seven grapes are permitted (sémillon, sauvignon blanc, muscadelle, plus ugni blanc, colombard, merlot blanc, and sauvignon gris), with the latter four generally found only in the less expensive wines. Among these, sémillon is noted as the most widely planted and significant for white Bordeaux wines.\n\nFor more details on specific varieties, refer to their descriptions in the provided guide (on page 53)."
