    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_269",
    "contenu": "The document discusses the roles of vitamins and phytochemicals in human health with a focus on antioxidants and their functions. Here's its structured content:\n\n### Plant Foods and Health\n\n- **Vitamins and Antioxidants Roles**:\n  - **Vitamin C** refreshes the chemical state of metal components in many enzymes, helps with the synthesis of connective-tissue collagen.\n  - **Vitamin A**, derived from beta-carotene, aids in eye functionality.\n  - **Folic Acid**, converts homocysteine into methionine, reducing the risk of blood vessel damage, heart disease, and stroke.\n  - Antioxidants include **Vitamin A, C, and E**.\n\n- **Phytochemicals**:\n  - Initial beliefs were centered around preventing vitamin and mineral deficiencies through adequate fruits and vegetables consumption.\n  - Modern nutritional science recognizes the broader biochemical roles that food components play in reducing risks of major diseases like cancer and heart disease.\n  - Plant-based diets now are seen to have a profound role in long-term health, primarily as sources of valuable antioxidants.\n\n- **Antioxidants and Oxidative Stress**:\n  - Oxidative damage results from the body’s energy generation, where free radicals generated damage cells and tissues.\n  - Examples given include cellular DNA damage that can lead to tumors, or UV rays causing skin and eye damage.\n  - Plants are highlighted as vital sources of antioxidants that protect against the continuous damage from these free radicals.\n\nThe overall content affirms a significant evolution in the understanding of nutrition from simply preventing deficiencies to enhancing long-term health through dietary components."
