    "contenu": "The content of the document pertains to alcohol in wine, focusing on its sources, effects, and categorizations based on alcohol content. Below is the structured breakdown of the key information presented in the text:\n\n### Alcohol in Wine\n- **Source of Alcohol**: The alcohol in wine is derived from yeast converting grape must (sugar) into ethanol. Additionally, alcohol can be added to wines in a process known as fortifying.\n\n### Influence of Alcohol\n- **Role in Wine Aromas**: Alcohol plays a significant role in the aromas of wine.\n- **Texture and Taste Sensations**: Alcohol contributes body and can influence the sensation of a wine in the mouth and throat. A \"hot\" wine, often described as having higher alcohol content, is notable for the burning sensation it might leave in the throat.\n\n### Categorization by Alcohol Content\n- **Medium Alcohol Content Wine**: Wines with an alcohol by volume (ABV) of 12.5% to 13.5%.\n- **High Alcohol Content Wine**: Wines with an ABV over 15% are considered bold or full-bodied.\n\n### Tips for Understanding Wine Styles:\n- **Comparison Tip**: To understand the difference in body due to alcohol content, one can compare light- to medium-bodied wines (similar in body to skim milk) versus full-bodied wines (similar in body to full cream milk).\n\nThe information is offered in a visual format with varying font sizes and orientations, enhancing the emphasis on certain aspects like the sensation of \"hot\" or \"full-bodied\" due to higher alcohol levels. Additionally, specific graphical elements like circles and wine glass icons are used to signify different levels of alcohol content."
