  {
    "source": "inconnu_1809",
    "contenu": "# IT’S A DOG’S LIFE NO, REALLY\n\nIn most places, a dog is a dog. But in a California vineyard, you might as well spell dog backward. In a vineyard, a dog realizes her higher calling. A good vineyard dog is, first and foremost, in charge of overall public relations. She (or he) greets—and loudly announces—all visitors. She then attends all wine tastings, pre-sampling the baguettes for freshness and occasionally resting her head in the lap of the taster so as to inspire creative descriptions of the wines being tasted. A vineyard dog is, of course, faithfully dusty from stalking mice, moles, wild turkeys, rabbits, and deer in the vineyard. She knows exactly when the vineyard crew stops for lunch, so as to help in the consumption of *burritos con pollo* and *tacos al pastor*. Above all, a good vineyard dog knows (this is true) when the grapes are ripe and will nibble a cluster right off the vine when the time is right.\n\nOn the other hand, many sites the world over provide excellent environments for two or more grape varieties that are fairly similar in their needs. For example, in both Bordeaux and northern California, cabernet sauvignon and merlot are often planted in adjoining vineyard blocks. If a site can support two or more similar varieties well, then planting those there can have advantages both in the vineyard and in the cellar. In the vineyard, multiple varieties can be an asset because grapes ripen at different rates. If the earlier-ripening grape is already picked when a devastating storm hits, the grower loses only a percentage of the crop. Many Old World vineyards, including the vineyards of Bordeaux, are planted with several varieties precisely as an economic hedge against bad weather. And in the cellar, the winemaker has more colors on the palette with which to paint."
  },
  {
    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_378",
    "contenu": "### A Survey of Common Fruits\n\n#### Verjus and Saba\nTwo ancient grape preparations make versatile ingredients in the kitchen. They involve fruits thinned six to eight weeks before the main harvest, crushed, and filtered to produce **verjus**, a tart alternative to vinegar or lemon juice, or cooked down to a thick, sweet-tart concoction known as **saba (Roman sapa, Italian saba or mosto cotto, Turkish pekmez, Arab dibs)**. Grape syrup was an important sweetener pre-sugar era, providing tartness and aroma as well as sweetness. During storage, it evolved from grape syrup to balsamic vinegar, thanks to long fermentation periods (p. 775).\n\n#### Kiwi\nThe fruit named after New Zealand growers is originally from the berry of a Chinese vine, **Actinidia deliciosa**. Kiwi fruits have thick, green skin and a distinctive translucent flesh with 1,500 tiny seeds. They are known for high vitamin C and carotenoids content and showcase unique ripening behaviors. Unlike other fruits, kiwis don't change color during ripening and develop stronger fruity esters that make their aromas and flavors more delicate over time.\n\n#### Mulberry\nA significant fruit from the **Morus** genus, mulberries are small and carry a resemblance to blackberries. Each mulberry consists of a small fruitlet connected to an individual flower on a short flowering stalk. The fruit is most flavorful in its dried form, especially the **Persian or black species, M. nigra**. They are primarily used in making preserves, syrups, and sorbets.\n\n#### Strawberry\nStrawberries belong to the genus **Fragaria** and are unique due to their reproduction method involving \"seeds\" which are actually dry fruits called achenes. Strawberries adapt well to diverse climates ranging from arctic regions to tropical zones. The fruit expands and changes texture due to internal growth pressures, which can be impacted negatively by dehydration or freezing.\n\n---\nEach fruit described has unique culinary properties and methods of cultivation, significantly influenced by their individual characteristics and historical cultivation methods."
  },
