    "source": "the-wine-bible-karen-macneil.pdf_page_1810",
    "contenu": "### New Zealand Wine Labeling Regulations\n\nIn New Zealand, while there is no stringent legal framework like the French **Appellation d'Origine Contrôlée** laws for wine making, there are specific regulations concerning the labeling and certain aspects of wine production. These regulations are enshrined in the country’s official Food Act and Food Regulations. Here’s a breakdown of the key rules:\n\n- **Variety Composition on Label**: If a grape variety or varieties are named on a wine label, at least 85% of the wine must be composed of the named variety or varieties. It is common practice in New Zealand to have wines that are 100% composed of the variety or varieties stated on the label.\n  \n- **Order of Varieties**: If two grapes are named on the label, they must be listed in order of their percentage composition. For example:\n  - **Cabernet-Merlot**: Contains more cabernet than merlot.\n  - **Merlot-Cabernet**: Contains more merlot than cabernet.\n  \n- **Geographical Indication**: When a geographic area, district, or region is specified on the label, a minimum of 85% of the wine must originate from that designated area.\n\nThese regulatory requirements ensure clarity and truthfulness in the labeling of wines, helping consumers make informed choices about the origins and compositions of their wine purchases."
  },
