    "source": "The_Art_of_Fermentation.pdf_page_478",
    "contenu": "This document describes a method for producing a type of Sudanese beer, called \"merissa,\" using a traditional sorghum beer method.\n\n### Ingredients:\n- 1 pound (500 g) of malted grain\n- 1 pound (500 g) of unmalted grain or sorghum grits/flour\n\n### Brew Volume:\nProduces about 1 gallon (4 liters) of sorghum beer.\n\n### Brew Ratio:\nThe ratio of malted grain to unmalted grain to water is 1:1:3.\n\n### Procedure:\n1. **Boiling the Grains:**\n   - Boil water and add unmalted sorghum grits/flour.\n   - Continue stirring to achieve a porridge-like consistency.\n2. **Cooling:**\n   - Remove from the heat and allow the porridge to cool to 140°F (60°C).\n3. **Adding Malted Grain:**\n   - Once the mixture is cool enough to comfortably touch, add half of the malted sorghum grits/flour, ensuring it's still quite warm.\n   - Stir thoroughly to integrate the malt.\n4. **Enzymatic Action:**\n   - The enzymes in malt are most efficient at about 140°F (60°C) and help digest complex carbohydrates into simple sugars.\n5. **Insulation:**\n   - Keep the mixture in a warm or insulated spot, protected from flies.\n6. **Further Cooling:**\n   - After a few hours, once the temperature drops below 110°F (43°C), add the second half of the malted grain.\n   - Stir well to distribute evenly.\n7. **Fermentation:**\n   - Allow the mix to remain in a warm spot for 12 to 24 hours. During this period, lactic acid bacteria proliferate, lowering the pH to create a selective environment beneficial for the beer brewing process.\n\nThis process combines careful temperature control, timing, and a two-stage addition of malted grains to optimize enzyme activity and flavor development in the beer."
