    "contenu": "The document appears to be a text discussing issues related to the growth and sensory qualities of tempeh and koji, which are both fermentation products. Here is the structured content of the document:\n\n### Java, Tempeh, and Koji\n\n**Tempeh Overview:**\n- In Java, an overripened tempeh is known as \"tempeh busuk\", and it is considered a delicacy.\n\n**Tempeh smells like ammonia:**\n- The initial 24 hours of mold growth in tempeh is characterized by a fresh, earthy smell.\n- As the mold overripens, it develops an ammonia smell. This stage is compared to the aroma of fine Camembert cheese, and tempeh's texture becomes softer and creamier.\n- William Shurtleff and Akiko Aoyagi have described this overripe aroma as remarkably like that of fine Camembert cheese.\n- The texture of the tempeh at this stage softens to a slightly creamy consistency.\n- It is suggested not to be afraid of trying overripe tempeh.\n\n**Mold fails to grow on koji:**\n- Failure of mold growth on \"koji\" could be due to:\n  - Non-viable starter.\n  - Inappropriate temperature of the grains when the starter was introduced.\n  - Inappropriate temperature of the incubation chamber.\n\n**Koji feels slimy:**\n- A slimy coating on koji indicates overheating during incubation.\n- As koji mold grows, it generates significant heat which can potentially kill the mold:\n  - This is especially likely if the inoculated substrate is thick, ventilation is limited, or a large batch of koji is in a small incubation chamber.\n- Normally, the spores of Bacillus subtilis are present and are heat-resistant. Even though Bacillus subtilis may be present in koji substrates, they are inhibited from developing significantly if the koji mold is still active. However, if the koji mold stops growing, Bacillus subtilis can develop. \n\nThis document provides insights into the fermentation processes and potential issues encountered with tempeh and koji."
