    "source": "The_Art_of_Fermentation.pdf_page_538",
    "contenu": "This document discusses the characteristics and storage methods of tempeh during and after fermentation. Here's a structured breakdown of the information provided in the text:\n\n### Document Overview: Characteristics and Storage of Tempeh\n\n#### Fermentation Process:\n- **Indicators**: There is no specific moment when fermentation is complete. Tempeh is considered formed once the mycelium growth binds the beans or grains into a cohesive mat.\n- **Ripeness**: Tempeh is ripe when dark patches begin to appear, indicating the onset of sporulation.\n\n#### Aroma and Flavor:\n- **Fresh Tempeh**: Yeasty or slightly mushroomy aroma and flavor.\n- **During Sporulation**: As sporulation progresses, the aroma and flavor become stronger and tinged with ammonia, similar to ripe cheese.\n- **Cultural Preferences**: The Javanese savor tempeh at various stages of sporulation, while a French individual noted in the text enjoys very ripe tempeh, comparing it to Camembert cheese.\n\n#### Storage Recommendations:\n1. **At Ambient Temperatures or in the Refrigerator**:\n   - Tempeh can continue to ferment, darkening and intensifying in ammonia aroma and flavor.\n   - It is highly perishable.\n   - Considered not a strategy for preservation if kept at ambient conditions.\n\n2. **In the West**:\n   - Tempeh for resale is typically frozen, often after being pasteurized by steaming.\n\n3. **Personal Practice of the Author**:\n   - Consumes some tempeh fresh immediately after removal from the incubation chamber.\n   - Stores tempeh in the refrigerator for a few days, ensuring it is spread out to maximize surface exposure to cool air.\n   - Freezes remaining tempeh if storing beyond a few days.\n\nBy detailing the fermentation characteristics, specific cultural perceptions, and practical storage methods, this document provides a comprehensive guide to handling and appreciating tempeh."
